utterances.utterance: Being out of this as a contributor was tying me to that horrific tragedy in El Paso was galling. And I just think we all have a right -- in America right to free speech. And I and a lot of people that support President Trump, we're not going to be called -- we're not going to be -- we're not going to be -- we're not going to be called racist and the other slurs without fighting back.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Dan, what do you think about that?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: You know, Donna, I disagree. It's time to take the L on this one. You just got to take the loss and admit that this was just dumb. at and made it was dumb. And the dumb test is would you do this to your opponent? I actually ran for office, didn't win, but took a shot three times, and the answer is never. In a million years when -- because if something happened to that person or their kids because some maniac found some kind of inspiration in it and decided to target that person. I would feel --

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: Dan.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: One more point of this. And this public nonsense, oh, it's public. OK. So is my website. But I spent a lot of money to advertise on my website, why? To make it easier to find for people. Putting it on your twitter account with people's names and their businesses and say, oh, well, it's public anyway, it's the lamest excuse ever. You're making these people easier to find by advertising --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I think -- and unfortunately, so I think there will be more of this. Julian Castro tweet today was Joaquin and I will keep fighting. The America people will fight every day for our nation against your hate, your corruption, and your ego, and we'll win, hashtag, adios Trump. I think that Castro doing that will actually encourage others to do it because you could go and find it.

utterances.speaker: LAWRENCE JONES, HOST
utterances.utterance: A hundred percent. And I think -- here's the bottomline. Hate has been associated with conservatives right now. If you're Republican, if you're conservative, and you think about the business, but what about on the local level, average day Americans that have to goat this. The University of Texas is going through this right now. The incoming freshman class are experiencing doxing. They're going to join a conservative group, their information is now being public. The attorney general for the state of Texas has now been asked to get involved by the University of Texas because this is happening. To kids, these were high schoolers, right? Incoming freshmen class. They're kids. And just because they want to join a conservative group they're being targeted? It's nonsense. And I think Democrats cozy up to these types of people. That's why when it comes to Antifa, they won't do it. The politicians will do it. Many of these politicians won't go and get in the face of people. But they say, well, they're hateful people. But when hate becomes synonymous now in their eyes of conservatives and Republicans, that becomes a big problem.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: What about-ism is what we practice today when we dislike what the other side is doing. There's a bigger issue here. The bigger issue is should we use social media platform to promote and to highlight and amplify hate? I said the other day when we -- when this first came out, that I would not have done it because I've been a victim, including from somebody at the very top of our food chain of using social media platforms, calling me out on false pretenses, and I know what it's like when people come after you. So, I'm not for this. But what I'm saying is that this information is publicly available. What the congressman did I believe has started a nonsense conversation over the -- you know, over media platforms and how they're being weaponized today. I don't believe in it and I don't believe this is just, you know, another case of a congressman trying to get attention. This was a stupid idea in a week when we're trying to focus on the healing of our country.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I think -- I mean, the point you make is true. Like, you don't want to make this week any worse than it is. People should wake up in the morning and go, OK, is what I'm about to do going to make it better or worse? And, I mean, unfortunately, a lot of people don't do that. I do think that -- you know, I'll just stop. I should take my own advice.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: But remember, a lot of those people were his donors too.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: What a dopey, stupid move to do. Remember that test, if you wouldn't do it to your opponent it's probably not the right thing to do.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Let's just not do it, people, let's not. All right, up next, Hollywood celebrities boycotting a gym over President Trump, and a new movie under fire for a plot line about targeting deplorables.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Hollywood hypocrites back at it again with some outrageous stories. First up, celebrities are boycotting Equinox and soul cycle over a Trump fund-raiser being held by the parent company's CEO. Trump-hater Chrissy Teigen tweeting, everyone who cancels their Equinox and sole cycle memberships, meet me at the library. Bring weights. The company is caving to their liberal clients, said they've nothing to do with the event and don't support it. But their billionaire boss is refusing to back down. Good. Good for him. Celebrities are the whiniest, grimiest, moaniest group of people out there. It is exhausting. Donna, will these people just -- they're not helping. Look what they did for Hillary Clinton? Remember those concerts before she got elected president?

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: We have celebrities come from both sides of the political aisle. I found that out when -- who was the guy behind the cheer?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Clint Eastwood.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: So celebrities come --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: That was funny. I love that.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: That's pretty good.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: For a celebrity to come out as a conservative takes bravery. A conservative coming out a liberal of Hollywood -- I mean, celebrities coming out as a liberal in Hollywood is basically -- they're just trying to play along because they know that helps their career, especially somebody like Teigen. I mean, she should not be the moral arbiter here, because if you ever seen her twitter feed, I mean, she's slut shaming, she makes fun of babies names, she makes fun of kids, she rips pregnant celebrities. And here -- I mean, it's easy also when you're a rich celebrity to shame employees about where they work. But they may not have the luxury of saying, you know, I'm not going to work in Equinox because the owner gives money to X. No, they don't have the luxury of making those decisions like Chrissy Teigen does, who doesn't have to worry about where her money comes from.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And has a personal trainer, I'm sure.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: But political brand boycotts are the new normal. This is what everyone is doing. I don't know if you go back to 2009, you're probably too young. You were very young.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I was young too, Donna.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: Greg, you and I came out the same crib. We just got separated. But there's no question that these celebrities -- what happens now in Hollywood is that after the 2009 -- there were people boycotting folks on one side of same-sex marriage and the other side the same-sex marriage. So every political cause today have celebrities who take positions and stand on one side or another. But this is about branding.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: But let me tell you why it's not smart with Equinox is liberals. I work out of Equinox every single day.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Where and what time?

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: I'm not telling you. Every single one in there --

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: You would be lucky because the political views --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Fox is not on.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: CNN, MSNBC. And one day when I tried to change they threw a fit about it.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: You'll see it in my gym. Shout out Power House. Don't change it. You're watching right now, Power House.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: I don't watch the news when I workout

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: And any liberal event they post it on the doors and try to get you to sign up for it, and I never --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: What happens if -- Like, I belong to Equinox, too. What if half the people stopped showing up, how great is that?

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: You are making the case for people to go to Equinox --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know what happened to me this morning. I'm going in to Equinox and I get stopped by this young, pleasant woman, and I go out here -- you know, she's like -- she goes, hey, do you work out here? And I thought she was going to try to get me to take up a personal training class because that's what they do, and I go, oh, no. Well, I'm so-and-so from the New Yorker and I would want -- see if I could talk to you about this and I said no, I can't. I don't think she recognized me. That is outrageous that she didn't know world-class celebrity right there.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: But I don't see conservatives booing when Colin Kaepernick signed on with Nike. I mean, no, everybody -- only conservative side were burning their tennis shoes and --

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: This is -- they can do whatever they want.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: But we don't call for boycott. I don't know anybody that calls for boycotts.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Also, another secret that happens at Equinox -- I go there too, for Pilates.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Do you know how many people come up to you and they say, like, by the way, you're my favorite.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: I know.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I watch Fox. I'm the only one who watches Fox. Like the secret conservatives.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: Are you all trying to tell me that only liberals go to gym?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: No, no, but I'll boycott --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: -- but liberal boycott typically blowup in their face. Listen, if Chick-fil-A sold stocks when liberals boycott, buy stocks at Chick-fil-A it's ridiculous. Liberal boycotts are horrendous. They never work.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: Conservatives do boycotts. Liberals go out there and take out -- they get more --

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: -- New York Times --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: All right, let's move on.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I'll eat anything and I will wear anything.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Equally disturbing. Hollywood liberals are now hunting down and killing deplorables for sport in a disturbing new movie, claims to be satire but it's being slammed as demented and evil. Take a look at this.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Your idea is incredible.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: You can argue with that. We pay for everything, so this country belongs to us.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: It's just business.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Hunting human beings for sport.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: What?

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: What?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Despite the backlash, Universal Pictures says it has no plans to stop the movie from being released --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Can I defend this because this is an old idea, the most dangerous game. There's a lot of movies about hunting humans and we have no idea who becomes victorious in this. This is a satire. I think -- oh, my God, they're hunting conservatives. I guarantee you the conservative will probably win and that's the twist in this. So I think this is much ado about nothing.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: This is publicity for them.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: They're not going to shelve it because --

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: I just hate the hypocrisy when it comes to the tone. Let's bring the tone down. It's on them. We get to make a movie about it, right?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That's a good point.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: I just hate that.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Go to twitter and just put in your name if you're on this network --

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: I always look at and see how many women and minorities because they often get kicked off first?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Like twitter?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No, no, she means in horror movies.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Donna, that's changed. I watch a lot of horror movies, it's changed. The white people get it first.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: The white people get it first?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: Things have changed.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: Hey, Greg.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: I want to make sure. Let's keep the black people in just for another hour, please.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Crazy Bernie's UFO clad, and vegan Cory Booker could be in trouble at the meat field Iowa state fair. That more in our 2020 roundup, stay tune.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: Time now for our 2020 roundup. First up, if you thought Bernie was a little off his rocker before, wait until you hear this. Sanders is promising to reveal information about aliens if he wins the White House. Watch.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: If you got into the office and you found out something about aliens, if you found out about something about UFO's, would you let us know?

utterances.speaker: SEN. BERNIE SANDERS, I-VT
utterances.utterance: I'll tell you. My wife would demand that I let you know.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Is your wife a UFO nut?

utterances.speaker: SANDERS
utterances.utterance: No, she's not a UFO -- just, Bernie, what is going on? You have any access --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: You don't have any access?

utterances.speaker: SANDERS
utterances.utterance: I honestly don't know.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: OK. You'll let us know, though?

utterances.speaker: SANDERS
utterances.utterance: All right, I'll be on this show -- I'll announce it on this show.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Please.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: So, Dana, he's apparently smoking, right? You see him --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I don't know because I've never smoked it and I don't know what it's like. But --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You only do the edibles, right?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I would say --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: -- he's trying to bribe for votes, right? Because people want this UFO information so badly, it's like I'll do it and then he'll probably won't because the CIA will stop him.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: There are UFO's, they're living in Bernie's hair. They're really, really microscopic. By the way, every president -- every candidate does do this, they say this, but then once they see the file their brains were erased. They erase it so they don't have any memory of it.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: I think it was a $22 million program that track -- it was cut out during the sequester. But I would be interested in knowing if there's some other people here.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: I don't believe it, Dan.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Listen, do you remember the Waco ranch, the bushes? If the moon was not -- it was pretty black. There was no moonlight coming out. That sky can get pretty black and you see some crazy stuff. You're like, what is that thing out there? But, yeah, Greg's right. Everyone says they're going to give us the big UFO file. There's no UFO file --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Listen, the government -- Father Bob -- had the greatest line of all. He says it's not the government. It's too big. It's too stupid. They can't keep a secret. You think there's -- I'm not suggesting that maybe UFO -- I'm just telling you do you think the government is keeping the secret?

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: How do you two not know? How many presidents you work for --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: People swore to me, you saw the real Zapruder film, you know who killed -- that's the film, man. I'm not lying to you --

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: The air force -- the navy reported seeing something right alongside --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: No, it was a fly.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That's what they want you to think, Dana.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: And also another unit saw something over Arizona. So there's something out there, we just don't know --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: I think Bernie is out there enough that if there was a UFO file, and God-forbid --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He could be a space alien.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: I will show you the file.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: Up next, talk about a bold strategy to win over voters, 2020 Democrat Michael Bennet taking to twitter promising he'll be boring and it's not a mistake. Bennet is actually defending the idea.

utterances.speaker: SEN. MICHAEL BENNET, D-COLO.
utterances.utterance: I think the American people would feel liberated if they could get up in the morning not wondering who the President of the United States was attacking by his tweets.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: And it looks like it's working because Bennet is polling at about zero percent.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: So this is like silent Cal, Cal Coolidge. Basically was like I am not going to screw anything up. I'm just going to be the caretaker of the government and everybody else go live your life. So I think he's trying for that role.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: But, Donna, nobody likes a boring president.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: I would take a boring president. In fact, I would take a boring vice president, too. Just along he or she is --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: That approach may have worked -- I don't know, 30, 40 years ago, but in the era of social media everybody wants -- plus, Trump is set with the presidency. It's never going to happen. We're done with the boring --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I think what -- I think this might be the best campaign promise for the moment now because we have to admit that for -- you know, Trump is like four presidencies wrapped in one. There's 17 stories a day. He's -- I would say he's the 3-hour drive to an hour at the beach. You get there the beach is great, but it's a rough ride, you know, because he attacks. He attacks. He attacks. So the idea of a boring president it's like putting on a nice comfy warm sweater. The problem is what is boring mean? Does that mean he won't -- he'll do exactly what the media wants him to do so there won't be any conflict, or that he'll do everything the establishment or the corporations want? I'm beginning to sound like Tucker. But what I'm saying is, it could be that he -- it could be great or else he could that he's ineffective and incompetent.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: Maybe we'll just return to norm. The old fashion --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: This is the new normal. The greatest president ever, Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: And finally, Cory Booker may be a little nervous after he and other Democratic candidates flocked to the Iowa state fair. It's known for the beef Sunday and legendary pork chop on a stick, but Booker is a vegan who has said eating meat will destroy the planet. What is he going to eat, Donna?

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: I did my research. Let's see, apple slices with fresh ground honey roasted peanut butter. What about a dill pickle?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: You really do have a list there.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: She's not kidding.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: I want to help my Democrats.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: No milk. No milk.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: No milk. Dill pickle popcorn, and then I found corn stalker cocktail. They say it will sneak up on you.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh, I hate those.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: I love fairs because you get the good food. But, Dana, I want to ask you, how much does Iowa play in the politics of, you know, the next Democratic nominee?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, the thing is, is that -- often, whoever wins Iowa doesn't necessarily go on to become the nominee, eventually, but it does give you a lot of momentum and bragging rights and then you can go and do some other things. Right now, as I understand it, the best organization is down in tie between Warren and Booker, if I'm correct.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: That is correct.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: So the vegan is doing well in Iowa, apparently.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: I've been to these things a lot. I would advise the candidates to go and see the butter cow, a butter cow, I'll bet you'll love it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I feel bad for Cory. Being a vegan at a state fair is like being a priest at a strip club.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Can I just say that I don't want to live in a planet without rabbis.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: I mean I'm sorry I don't want to do that. But you can really screw that up you know. Remember - you ever see the National Geographic episode Air Force One, where Obama gets on the plane and he asked the guy about the Grey Poupon, like you can really screw that up, the food, you just have to ask for mustard. Like the cameras obviously, you don't get--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Did that really happened.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Yes, I swear. He asked you've got the Grey Poupon stuff and the guy, yes, we got the Grey Poupon.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I'm a Grey Poupon guy.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: What about fried Oreos?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: It's great.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I'll take them. I'll eat anything that's not fish as you know.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: Donna, one thing we've been hearing a little bit about is Kamala's first TV ad today. What do you think about that?

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: I think they are really good. I think it will help her to reignite and refocus her campaign.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: She was low energy last time.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: I think it looked like she didn't get enough sleep, or maybe she was over--

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: Yes, because Tulsi brought it to her like Joe did.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: But you know what, I wouldn't mess with a prosecutor.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: Oh! You heard it from Donna. Up next, the UN has a new plan to save the planet in 2020, Dems will love it. But will you though. More on “The Five.”

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: The United Nations is out with a new report about fighting climate change. It says people should start eating less meat, Greg, and more vegetables in order to save the planet. Greg--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I'm against this obviously.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: Cows produce a lot of methane gas.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: So, do I. You want to kill me too. You know, there is evidence that vegetables feel pain. You know broccoli exudes that odor because it's trying to fend off people. Yes. So. So, I'm more concerned about the pain of the vegetables and what happens if we stop eating meat. Suddenly billions of animals will just be hanging around. And this happened to mules and horses right after we got cars. Where are the mules and horses go? They went away. They went away.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: But--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I have no science to back this up.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: This report, 100 experts from 52 countries. It really - it's a wakeup call because it's essentially saying with rising temperatures extreme weather events you know floods, storms et cetera is impacting the Earth and it could impact our food supply.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: Is it bad if I don't care.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: Yes. You should.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: Literally, I don't care because I want my meat and I believe that it was placed on here for us to eat. And I think it's a minimal effect on the world compared to all of the other gases--

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: There is other way to get protein.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: I don't what it though. I don't like that protein. I like beef. I like chicken and I love; they cook very well. And I just think it's a selfish argument. Plus, I don't care what the UN says anyway. BRAZILE: You don't care about climate change. This is experts--

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: Climate changes all the time. We're changing the climate.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: Yes, we're in a wake-up period. If we - if the Earth continues at this pace--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: In 10 years, it's gone.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: We'll all be dead.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: No-

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Earth just been flat for 18 years.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: We're going to face a shortage of food.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: No, we won't.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.utterance: We're going to see--
